{
  "text": "However, as pointed out in [CITATION_1] , the actual anonymity offered is less than this ideal value and is equal to number of distinct values in each equivalence class. We call this as the effective anonymity For each target individual i, EAij is the effective prior anonymity with respect to Rj (anonymity before the intersection attack). In the intersection attack, the list of possible sensitive values associated to the target is equal to intersection of all sensitive value sets sij , j = 1, . . . , n. So the effective posterior anonymity ( c EAi) for i is:",
